WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.200
All right.

00:00:13.200 --> 00:00:15.400
Thank you all for coming to this session.

00:00:15.400 --> 00:00:18.719
This will be the tidyverse session, and I have the pleasure of introducing Karthik Ram

00:00:18.719 --> 00:00:19.719
for our first speaker.

00:00:19.719 --> 00:00:23.480
He'll be going over a guide to reproducible analysis.

00:00:23.480 --> 00:00:24.480
Thank you.

00:00:24.480 --> 00:00:25.480
All right.

00:00:25.480 --> 00:00:26.480
Thank you, Sean.

00:00:26.480 --> 00:00:27.480
Okay.

00:00:27.480 --> 00:00:44.360
Today I'm going to give you a talk about how to make your data science notebook or just

00:00:44.360 --> 00:00:48.400
about any R project that you might have a little bit more reproducible than it already

00:00:48.400 --> 00:00:49.880
is.

00:00:49.880 --> 00:00:55.560
And I just want to point out that at the end of my talk I will give you a link to a GitHub

00:00:55.560 --> 00:01:01.799
repo that contains all of the links, the readme, other demos and tutorials and so on.

00:01:01.799 --> 00:01:05.879
So feel free to listen and not take notes just yet.

00:01:05.879 --> 00:01:09.919
So this is a situation that I frequently find myself in.

00:01:09.919 --> 00:01:12.440
I find a cool project on GitHub.

00:01:12.440 --> 00:01:13.900
I try to clone it.

00:01:13.900 --> 00:01:18.440
I can see that they've got a few packages listed, a few datasets mentioned.

00:01:18.440 --> 00:01:22.959
But even if I'm able to install those packages, the code doesn't quite work correctly and

00:01:22.959 --> 00:01:27.680
I start debugging and things don't quite work, and I don't have a beautiful R markdown at

00:01:27.680 --> 00:01:28.680
the end.

00:01:28.680 --> 00:01:33.959
I just have a very, very sad GitHub repo with lots of errors, and then I just move on to

00:01:33.959 --> 00:01:35.559
something else.

00:01:35.559 --> 00:01:42.360
And so the main thing I want to talk to you about today is this idea of a research compendium.

00:01:42.360 --> 00:01:49.839
And this is an idea that was put forth back in 2004 by Robert Gentleman and Duncan Temple-Lang.

00:01:49.839 --> 00:01:55.599
And the general idea was that you can create sort of this container for your data, your

00:01:55.599 --> 00:02:02.879
code and your text, but also take advantage of software engineering principles to make

00:02:02.879 --> 00:02:08.539
sure that this package that you have or compendium that you have can easily be maintained, updated

00:02:08.539 --> 00:02:10.720
and then shared with everyone else.

00:02:10.720 --> 00:02:15.460
And so what I want to encourage you after this talk is to go back and set up a compendium

00:02:15.460 --> 00:02:23.360
for your project as a way to make it easily shareable and useful to other people.

00:02:23.360 --> 00:02:29.100
Even though setting up a compendium was very complex and painful back in 2004, thanks to

00:02:29.100 --> 00:02:33.619
Tidyverse plus DevTools and friends, it's a lot easier to do now.

00:02:33.619 --> 00:02:44.759
And so Ben Marwick, Carl Bettinger and Lincoln Mellon wrote a very nice paper last year on

00:02:44.759 --> 00:02:49.559
how to set up a research compendium or a practical guide to setting up a research compendium.

00:02:49.559 --> 00:02:54.119
And I just want to talk through a few of these ideas that came out of that paper.

00:02:54.119 --> 00:02:58.479
The first one being that you should just organize your project in a way that makes sense to

00:02:58.479 --> 00:02:59.479
you.

00:02:59.479 --> 00:03:02.399
There are no hard and fast rules about how to set up a compendium.

00:03:02.399 --> 00:03:07.059
Many of you attended Jim and Jenny's workshop over the last couple of days on how to set

00:03:07.059 --> 00:03:08.820
up your R projects.

00:03:08.820 --> 00:03:12.580
All the advice you got from there is excellent for a compendium.

00:03:12.580 --> 00:03:17.179
And so just do it in a way that makes sense for people that you might collaborate with.

00:03:17.179 --> 00:03:22.500
Once you've got that going for you, make sure you have all of your code and your data and

00:03:22.500 --> 00:03:26.500
all of the artifacts separate from the outputs that you might want to generate.

00:03:26.500 --> 00:03:30.339
One way to do this for data, for example, especially if it's quite small, is to just

00:03:30.440 --> 00:03:33.679
have a data raw folder inside of your compendium.

00:03:33.679 --> 00:03:38.199
And then the last bit that is not necessarily about Docker itself, although I'll spend most

00:03:38.199 --> 00:03:43.919
of my time talking about Docker, is figure out some way to describe your computing environment

00:03:43.919 --> 00:03:49.479
as well as you can so that someone in the future can actually run your analysis or then

00:03:49.479 --> 00:03:52.720
extend it one way or another.

00:03:52.720 --> 00:03:59.259
And so to make your compendium shareable and useful, you have to have four separate things.

00:03:59.259 --> 00:04:04.179
One is make sure there's a license that tells people how to use it.

00:04:04.179 --> 00:04:07.740
Make sure it's under some kind of version control, preferably Git.

00:04:07.740 --> 00:04:11.300
Make sure there's enough metadata as part of your compendium.

00:04:11.300 --> 00:04:16.579
And then the last thing, which is often ignored everywhere, is that you need to have a long-term

00:04:16.579 --> 00:04:17.820
archive.

00:04:17.820 --> 00:04:23.220
So GitHub is not a long-term archive, but Zenodo.org, for example, is a long-term place

00:04:23.220 --> 00:04:28.899
where you can deposit your compendium so that it continues to persist even after GitHub

00:04:28.899 --> 00:04:32.640
disappears or any other services disappear.

00:04:32.640 --> 00:04:37.700
So it turns out that the R package structure is already a very fantastic way to organize

00:04:37.700 --> 00:04:42.859
a compendium, and there's not really very much that you need to do.

00:04:42.859 --> 00:04:50.339
So many of you in the room are package developers or everyone in this room is a package user.

00:04:50.339 --> 00:04:53.660
And so if you've ever looked at the contents of an R package, you might see a description

00:04:53.660 --> 00:04:55.500
file that looks like this.

00:04:55.500 --> 00:05:00.500
This is a standard Debian control format that contains a lot of generally useful metadata.

00:05:00.500 --> 00:05:05.220
It has a title, an author, a version number, a date, and then somewhere in the bottom it

00:05:05.220 --> 00:05:09.859
contains useful bits like these are the dependencies for this project.

00:05:09.859 --> 00:05:14.140
But since everybody is binge-watching Marie Kondo on Netflix, I can make a Marie Kondo

00:05:14.140 --> 00:05:18.980
reference and say, Marie Kondo, the shit out of this file, and just make it a very, very

00:05:18.980 --> 00:05:21.500
minimal description file.

00:05:21.500 --> 00:05:25.940
You just need to say that it's a compendium, have a title, possibly a version number, and

00:05:25.940 --> 00:05:32.100
just your dependencies that are either on CRAN or CRAN plus GitHub.

00:05:32.100 --> 00:05:37.739
Simply adding this file to a project and calling it a description file makes it a compendium,

00:05:37.739 --> 00:05:40.540
and you already have a research compendium now.

00:05:40.540 --> 00:05:45.059
And once you turn something into a compendium, now you can take advantage of DevTools and

00:05:45.059 --> 00:05:46.059
Friends.

00:05:46.059 --> 00:05:52.500
So DevTools can help you make sure that your packages or your compendium can be installed.

00:05:52.500 --> 00:05:57.299
You can take advantage of all the tools that help you generate documentation and websites

00:05:57.299 --> 00:06:01.459
and also link everything up to continuous integration services to make sure that your

00:06:01.459 --> 00:06:06.359
compendium is still working over time.

00:06:06.359 --> 00:06:08.619
So how do you set up a compendium?

00:06:08.619 --> 00:06:10.500
Depends on the scale of your project.

00:06:10.500 --> 00:06:15.779
If you have a very simple analysis that is just a simple R Markdown notebook, you can

00:06:15.779 --> 00:06:21.619
have this very minimal structure, just a description, a readme file, a license, and then the key

00:06:21.619 --> 00:06:25.420
bits here that are different than a package are that you have a folder containing your

00:06:25.420 --> 00:06:30.179
R Markdown file and then a data folder containing, say, a small amount of data.

00:06:30.179 --> 00:06:35.700
And this would work for a small project or a small report, but then for a lot of you,

00:06:35.700 --> 00:06:39.299
you might end up with a slightly more complex compendium.

00:06:39.299 --> 00:06:43.420
So the only thing that's different here from the previous version is that you have decided

00:06:43.420 --> 00:06:46.619
to write a few custom functions for this project.

00:06:46.619 --> 00:06:51.739
And this is a situation where these functions are not broadly useful outside the scope of

00:06:51.739 --> 00:06:55.279
this project, which is why you haven't written a package.

00:06:55.279 --> 00:07:00.459
So these exist within the compendium, and now you have a namespace file that captures

00:07:00.459 --> 00:07:02.339
some of these dependencies.

00:07:02.339 --> 00:07:06.779
But for a lot of you, your actual real-world long-term research project is going to be

00:07:06.779 --> 00:07:08.500
far more complex.

00:07:08.500 --> 00:07:12.660
So in this case, you have taken all of your functions and moved those out into a separate

00:07:12.660 --> 00:07:16.980
package except for a few that are critical only to this project.

00:07:16.980 --> 00:07:20.899
But the new elements that you'll start to see are that you have issues with keeping

00:07:20.899 --> 00:07:24.299
track of all of the outputs that you have to generate, all of the scripts that you have

00:07:24.299 --> 00:07:25.619
to deal with.

00:07:25.619 --> 00:07:28.239
So you need some sort of workflow.

00:07:28.239 --> 00:07:30.619
And in this case, that is a makefile.

00:07:30.619 --> 00:07:35.820
And then because your project's dependencies can change over time and packages can change

00:07:35.820 --> 00:07:40.420
over time and the same package can have API changes over time, you need to capture your

00:07:40.420 --> 00:07:41.420
computing environment.

00:07:41.420 --> 00:07:43.940
And in that case, I have a Docker file.

00:07:43.940 --> 00:07:50.820
So you will have to decide what level of complexity you want for your compendium.

00:07:50.820 --> 00:07:56.739
And so for the rest of my talk, I want to focus on three separate components of a compendium

00:07:56.739 --> 00:08:00.540
and how to think about them and how to use tools for that particular purpose.

00:08:00.540 --> 00:08:02.100
I'd like to talk about data.

00:08:02.500 --> 00:08:03.500
I'm from industry.

00:08:03.500 --> 00:08:05.980
I don't have any good answers or solutions from you.

00:08:05.980 --> 00:08:09.100
You've already got a data engineering team that can help you.

00:08:09.100 --> 00:08:13.619
So the advice that I have is mostly for small to medium-sized projects.

00:08:13.619 --> 00:08:16.179
The second one is how to isolate your computing environment.

00:08:16.179 --> 00:08:21.459
And then the third one is talking about simple and complex workflows.

00:08:21.459 --> 00:08:22.880
So I'll start with data.

00:08:22.880 --> 00:08:27.100
So how do you manage data in the context of, like, a small to a medium-sized project?

00:08:27.100 --> 00:08:32.659
Well, a very simple answer is if the data are small enough, they're just tabular data,

00:08:32.659 --> 00:08:36.260
you can stick them inside of your compendium itself.

00:08:36.260 --> 00:08:40.500
Because GitHub lets you have files up to 150 megabytes each, and a compendium is not a

00:08:40.500 --> 00:08:45.500
package that is going to go on CRAN, you can just have arbitrary data files.

00:08:45.500 --> 00:08:49.520
And if you want to keep things very useful, you can even have a data raw folder that contains

00:08:49.520 --> 00:08:53.820
the raw data and then some scripts that turn it into useful data.

00:08:53.820 --> 00:08:58.580
If you write a package alongside your compendium and you want it to go on CRAN, you can include

00:08:58.580 --> 00:09:04.020
data in there, but your overall package size cannot exceed 5 megabytes.

00:09:04.020 --> 00:09:08.140
Nick Tierney and I started poking around all the data that exists inside of CRAN packages,

00:09:08.140 --> 00:09:13.340
and right now about 37% of them have a ton of data in there, and some projects have hundreds

00:09:13.340 --> 00:09:17.859
of tabular data files that are shipped inside of an R package.

00:09:17.859 --> 00:09:22.460
So that is one simple, easy solution that is often overlooked.

00:09:22.460 --> 00:09:25.979
Another one that I want to talk about is this fun little package by Carl Bettinger

00:09:25.979 --> 00:09:32.020
called Piggyback, and Piggyback allows you to attach arbitrary files, these can be any

00:09:32.020 --> 00:09:38.500
kind of files, up to 2 gigabytes each, and as many files as you would like to a GitHub

00:09:38.500 --> 00:09:39.580
release.

00:09:39.580 --> 00:09:41.020
So what is a GitHub release?

00:09:41.020 --> 00:09:45.460
If you have written software before and you release a new version of your software, you

00:09:45.460 --> 00:09:47.659
can tag a release on GitHub.

00:09:47.659 --> 00:09:54.380
When you do that, you get binaries attached, and Piggyback just allows you to attach more

00:09:54.380 --> 00:10:00.260
data files on to that release, and the functionality for this package is very, very simple.

00:10:00.260 --> 00:10:01.419
There are only five functions.

00:10:01.419 --> 00:10:06.299
You can create a new release for your repo, tag it with a version number, and then just

00:10:06.299 --> 00:10:11.059
upload whatever files that you would like to upload, and when you do that and go to

00:10:11.059 --> 00:10:18.140
the release section of your GitHub repo, it's just your repo slash release, or releases,

00:10:18.140 --> 00:10:20.700
you can see these files show up there.

00:10:20.700 --> 00:10:25.219
So you can set up your compendium in such a way that when you're running the code, you

00:10:25.219 --> 00:10:29.979
can have all these files downloaded back straight from GitHub, and because GitHub is a very

00:10:29.979 --> 00:10:35.260
fast CDN, you can get access to these files pretty easily, no matter where you're running

00:10:35.260 --> 00:10:37.460
your compendium.

00:10:37.460 --> 00:10:43.419
If you've got a medium data situation where you have a large number of highly compressed

00:10:43.419 --> 00:10:48.320
text files that contain data locally, you can use this package called ArcDB that is

00:10:48.320 --> 00:10:56.739
built upon DBI, and it allows you to chunk the data using your memory limits in and out

00:10:56.739 --> 00:10:59.900
of any database backend that DBI supports.

00:10:59.900 --> 00:11:05.559
So this is a nice way to either get lots of data back from a database, or if you've already

00:11:05.559 --> 00:11:11.559
acquired data through some other means, this is a way to use the limitations of your setup

00:11:11.559 --> 00:11:16.400
to get data into a database.

00:11:16.400 --> 00:11:20.400
The next bit I want to talk about is isolating your computing environment, and this is really

00:11:20.400 --> 00:11:25.719
important because even I can never actually run any of my old analysis, especially things

00:11:25.719 --> 00:11:30.039
that involve ggplot2 from last year or the year before or the year before that.

00:11:30.039 --> 00:11:31.239
I have all the packages.

00:11:31.239 --> 00:11:34.440
The code looks the same, but nothing really runs.

00:11:35.200 --> 00:11:39.280
This is a paper in Nature Biotechnology that talks about how having just different versions

00:11:39.280 --> 00:11:45.840
of R can produce entirely different results from your same analysis or your same code.

00:11:45.840 --> 00:11:50.400
So those of you that are familiar with Docker, Docker is a very nice way to just containerize

00:11:50.400 --> 00:11:55.760
your existing environment so that even if you change machines or upgrade machines or

00:11:55.760 --> 00:11:59.960
move organizations, you should still be able to run the same code with the same set of

00:11:59.960 --> 00:12:04.080
dependencies and then get the same output back.

00:12:04.080 --> 00:12:09.479
And adding a Docker file to your existing R project is quite easy these days.

00:12:09.479 --> 00:12:11.919
There's an R package called containerit.

00:12:11.919 --> 00:12:13.520
It's not on CRAN yet.

00:12:13.520 --> 00:12:19.679
It's only on GitHub, but it can take any arbitrary folder or get repo and generate a nice Docker

00:12:19.679 --> 00:12:21.640
file for you.

00:12:21.640 --> 00:12:26.919
The Jupyter project from the Jupyter Notebook team has a more general solution called repo

00:12:26.919 --> 00:12:31.599
to Docker that will do it for either a Python project or an R project or projects that contain

00:12:31.599 --> 00:12:33.159
both.

00:12:33.239 --> 00:12:36.599
And adding a Docker file to your project has many advantages.

00:12:36.599 --> 00:12:41.919
One very simple straight up one is that you can then Dockerize that particular project,

00:12:41.919 --> 00:12:45.619
launch a container, run your analysis, and then get back out.

00:12:45.619 --> 00:12:49.640
But I want to spend a few minutes talking about this fantastic open source project called

00:12:49.640 --> 00:12:53.479
Binder, or I should rather say Binder Hub.

00:12:53.479 --> 00:12:59.919
Binder Hub is an open source project that allows you to launch a live notebook from

00:12:59.919 --> 00:13:06.159
any GitHub repo on demand and let someone else run this analysis, poke through your

00:13:06.159 --> 00:13:10.679
code, make some changes, see the results for themselves, and then when they close the browser

00:13:10.679 --> 00:13:14.200
window, that particular instance is immediately killed off.

00:13:14.200 --> 00:13:26.000
And because it's easier to show you how this thing

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:29.760
works, this is an example real project from my collaborator Carl.

00:13:29.760 --> 00:13:33.000
I'm not on this particular collaboration.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:43.760
There's a button called launch Binder, which once I click will either build a Docker image

00:13:43.760 --> 00:13:49.080
for the first time or if it's already found an image from before, pull it out of the cache

00:13:49.080 --> 00:13:54.159
and then go on to install any other additional R packages that you might need that is not

00:13:54.159 --> 00:13:59.559
already captured in the Docker file and then drop you into an RStudio server.

00:13:59.559 --> 00:14:05.119
And as it's par for a live demo, it doesn't actually work as quickly as you expect it

00:14:05.119 --> 00:14:06.119
to.

00:14:06.119 --> 00:14:12.400
But in about 30 seconds or maybe a few minutes, this will actually drop you into a RStudio

00:14:12.400 --> 00:14:13.400
server.

00:14:13.400 --> 00:14:18.799
I'm just going to let that run while I go back to my talk.

00:14:18.799 --> 00:14:20.559
Yeah.

00:14:20.559 --> 00:14:24.280
And so you end up in an RStudio server now, and here are the two beautiful things that

00:14:24.280 --> 00:14:25.679
are happening.

00:14:25.679 --> 00:14:29.400
All of the R packages that you need for this analysis have already been installed, and

00:14:29.400 --> 00:14:32.679
all of your scripts, data, and code have already been copied in.

00:14:32.679 --> 00:14:36.000
And there's nothing more to do other than to open up a notebook and then start running

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:38.000
through it.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:43.799
And the way this works is that JupyterHub does 80% of this work, and BinderHub just

00:14:43.799 --> 00:14:45.840
does a little bit of coordination.

00:14:45.840 --> 00:14:50.039
It reads in a repo, sees if there's a Docker file, if there's a Docker file, it checks

00:14:50.039 --> 00:14:52.000
to see if there's a Docker image.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:56.840
If not, it builds one and then hands it off to JupyterHub to allocate some resources to

00:14:56.840 --> 00:14:59.119
it and launch a server on demand.

00:14:59.119 --> 00:15:00.559
This service is free.

00:15:00.559 --> 00:15:05.719
And then mybinder.org is an example of a BinderHub.

00:15:05.719 --> 00:15:08.000
And so how do you set this up for your R project?

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:11.719
Well, there are many different ways to do this, and in fact, I'm not going to go through

00:15:11.719 --> 00:15:15.640
all the different ways because that is going to be part of my readme.

00:15:15.960 --> 00:15:21.080
A simple way is just to add a text file called runtime.txt and then add R and then a particular

00:15:21.080 --> 00:15:27.719
date that corresponds to the version of R that you might want to capture.

00:15:27.719 --> 00:15:33.280
This also means that the Rocker project will pull all the CRAN packages that correspond

00:15:33.280 --> 00:15:34.940
to this exact date.

00:15:34.940 --> 00:15:38.640
So if your project moves along or your system moves along, everything will be locked in

00:15:38.640 --> 00:15:39.960
time.

00:15:39.960 --> 00:15:44.239
And then you have another text file called install.r that just contains a list of package

00:15:44.640 --> 00:15:45.799
install commands.

00:15:45.799 --> 00:15:49.000
This is the simple, most basic way to set this up.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:54.559
Then you can go to mybinder.org, paste the URL for your GitHub repo, click launch, add

00:15:54.559 --> 00:15:59.359
that Binder button, and then you should be good to go.

00:15:59.359 --> 00:16:08.000
So this is the basic approach, adding an install.r, runtime.txt, and then if you want to add any

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:11.679
Linux dependencies, you can add an app.txt.

00:16:11.679 --> 00:16:15.239
The only downside is it's very slow and every time you change anything, it will take hours

00:16:15.239 --> 00:16:17.880
to rebuild your Docker image.

00:16:17.880 --> 00:16:21.599
But then there's a faster way to do this is by adding a Docker file using one of those

00:16:21.599 --> 00:16:25.919
two packages, like container.it or repo.docker.

00:16:25.919 --> 00:16:30.719
And because we're going to use a Docker image that already contains tidyverse, things will

00:16:30.719 --> 00:16:32.719
move along very quickly.

00:16:32.719 --> 00:16:36.840
And then the pro option is because now you're all experts on Research Compendia and you

00:16:36.840 --> 00:16:41.080
already have a description file, then you just need to add a very, very short Docker

00:16:41.080 --> 00:16:42.080
file.

00:16:42.080 --> 00:16:46.400
It could even just be four lines that says start at this base image, move all my files

00:16:46.400 --> 00:16:53.200
into my container, and then install these few additional packages for my description.

00:16:53.200 --> 00:16:58.760
Those of you that don't know about the Rocker project, it contains daily versions of different

00:16:58.760 --> 00:17:03.340
instances of R, including ones that contain RStudio and then specialized ones for geospatial

00:17:03.340 --> 00:17:06.119
data and so on.

00:17:06.119 --> 00:17:09.040
The last bit of that I want to talk about are workflows.

00:17:09.040 --> 00:17:15.479
So I imagine that a lot of people in this room are quite familiar with Makefiles, and

00:17:15.479 --> 00:17:19.719
Carl Broman, who's here in this room, has a fantastic tutorial on Makefiles.

00:17:19.719 --> 00:17:23.680
And so having a Makefile somewhere inside of your compendium allows you to keep track

00:17:23.680 --> 00:17:26.719
of all of your scripts and all of your inputs and outputs.

00:17:26.719 --> 00:17:31.359
But those of you that have used Makefiles probably know that it can get cumbersome very,

00:17:31.359 --> 00:17:33.760
very quickly.

00:17:33.760 --> 00:17:36.680
The wildcard syntax is not intuitive to remember.

00:17:36.680 --> 00:17:39.239
Like I have to Google this thing every damn time.

00:17:39.239 --> 00:17:44.000
And then it generates so much output that it just clutters your compendium every single

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:45.760
time you run something.

00:17:45.760 --> 00:17:50.000
So I want to give a shout out to a fantastic project called Drake, which is also part of

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:51.520
ROpenSci.

00:17:51.520 --> 00:17:54.599
The author for this project, Will Landau, is in the room somewhere, and you should go

00:17:54.599 --> 00:17:57.920
talk to him if you're interested in talking about Drake.

00:17:57.920 --> 00:18:04.680
And what Drake is, is if you want to think about a piece of software that mimics Make

00:18:04.680 --> 00:18:08.040
but it's very R-centric, that's what Drake is.

00:18:08.040 --> 00:18:12.760
And Drake stands for Data Frames in R for Make.

00:18:12.760 --> 00:18:16.479
And of course, it is impossible for me to do a demo in the amount of time that I have

00:18:16.479 --> 00:18:17.479
left.

00:18:17.479 --> 00:18:21.479
But I want to mention that what Drake allows you to do is generate these very, very complex

00:18:21.479 --> 00:18:23.859
Makefiles without writing them out.

00:18:23.859 --> 00:18:29.400
It does beautiful wildcard expansions and then takes advantage of numerous parallel

00:18:29.400 --> 00:18:32.000
backends including things like future.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:37.040
It gives you a nice dependency graph with all of your inputs expanded.

00:18:37.040 --> 00:18:39.800
And then it'll also estimate runtimes.

00:18:39.800 --> 00:18:45.439
And because it uses a system called Store, S-T-O-R-R, as the backend, it does not clutter

00:18:45.439 --> 00:18:48.959
your entire environment and allows you to quickly read outputs back as and when you

00:18:48.959 --> 00:18:50.359
need them.

00:18:50.359 --> 00:18:54.280
And then this would be a beautiful dependency graph that it generates.

00:18:54.280 --> 00:18:55.359
It's an interactive graph.

00:18:55.359 --> 00:19:02.400
You can actually see runtimes, missing objects, and all the relationships in your workflow.

00:19:02.400 --> 00:19:07.400
So having Drake as part of your compendium instead of a Makefile can be a nice way for

00:19:07.400 --> 00:19:09.579
you to scale very large projects.

00:19:09.579 --> 00:19:13.880
And then the author will actually develop this for a real-world use case for a very

00:19:13.880 --> 00:19:17.439
complex Bayesian analysis project.

00:19:17.439 --> 00:19:19.680
So I have two take-home messages for you.

00:19:19.680 --> 00:19:25.319
One is that turning your project into a research compendium is as simple as throwing in a disk

00:19:25.319 --> 00:19:26.479
description file in there.

00:19:26.479 --> 00:19:29.719
And it can be a very, very minimal description file.

00:19:29.719 --> 00:19:32.719
The tiny bits of metadata, dependencies.

00:19:32.719 --> 00:19:38.119
And then you can use these modern tools like Binder to launch notebooks that make it more

00:19:38.119 --> 00:19:41.319
accessible for people trying to understand your analysis.

00:19:41.319 --> 00:19:45.640
But at the same time, all these solutions like Binder and Piggyback are designed to

00:19:45.640 --> 00:19:46.839
help you.

00:19:46.839 --> 00:19:50.839
But I cannot guarantee that GitHub will remain around forever or Binder will remain around

00:19:50.839 --> 00:19:51.839
forever.

00:19:51.839 --> 00:19:58.520
But, for example, having your data exported in some flat file format and throwing it in

00:19:58.520 --> 00:20:01.439
Zenodo would be a nice long-term archive.

00:20:01.439 --> 00:20:05.199
But for the short term, Piggyback will help you in your analysis pretty quickly.

00:20:05.199 --> 00:20:06.359
Same thing with Binder.

00:20:06.359 --> 00:20:10.719
Binder will just look for the Docker file, launch a beautiful RStudio server.

00:20:10.719 --> 00:20:14.520
And if Binder ever goes away, you still have a Docker file, and I think Docker will still

00:20:14.520 --> 00:20:16.800
be around for another five years.

00:20:16.800 --> 00:20:22.079
And then Drake also conveniently exports the entire workflow out of Drake into just

00:20:22.079 --> 00:20:25.760
basic R. So at some point you have a collaborator who hates Drake.

00:20:25.760 --> 00:20:27.520
Just pull the whole thing out.

00:20:27.520 --> 00:20:29.680
So that is my talk.

00:20:29.680 --> 00:20:32.640
And this is where I would like to get you to.

00:20:32.640 --> 00:20:33.640
Everything beautifully works.

00:20:33.640 --> 00:20:36.199
And the last bit is a Docker file in there.

00:20:36.199 --> 00:20:41.640
And then I have a very detailed readme here that includes a lot of links and stuff.

00:20:41.640 --> 00:20:42.640
So thank you.

00:20:42.719 --> 00:20:43.719
Thank you.

00:20:43.719 --> 00:20:44.719
Thank you.

00:20:44.719 --> 00:20:45.719
And have a great evening.

00:20:45.719 --> 00:20:46.719
Thank you.

00:20:46.719 --> 00:20:46.719


